excerpt: 82-hectare botanical garden with sculptures, a swan lake & significant collection of tropical trees.
detail_description: The Singapore Botanic Gardens, established in 1860 and listed as a UNESCO World Heritage site, spans 82 hectares of tropical paradise. It features lush lawns, ancient rainforests, tranquil lakes, and themed gardens. The National Orchid Garden within the premises showcases the world's largest collection of tropical orchids. For families, there's the Jacob Ballas Children's Garden with interactive features.
name: Singapore Botanic Gardens

excerpt: Vibrant island with sandy beaches, hotels & a casino, plus golf courses, a theme park & aquarium.
detail_description: Sentosa Island, located off the southern coast of Singapore, is a popular tourist destination known for its beautiful beaches, theme parks, and adventure activities. The island offers a wide range of attractions including Fort Siloso, Fort Siloso Skywalk, Butterfly Park & Insect Kingdom. Visitors can also enjoy upscale hotels and resorts with various dining options serving local and international cuisine. Sentosa Cove is a residential area on the island featuring luxurious mansions and condominium complexes with stunning sea views.
name: Sentosa

excerpt: A network of modern greenhouses & waterfront parks containing super trees lined with solar cells.
detail_description: Gardens by the Bay is a stunning showcase of modern horticulture and innovative design, nestled in the heart of Singapore. This expansive green space features towering supertrees adorned with solar panels, creating a futuristic atmosphere that feels like stepping into another world. Visitors can explore cooled indoor gardens and themed areas celebrating Singapore's rich cultural diversity, including Malay, Chinese, and Indian influences. While wandering through this urban oasis is free, certain attractions like the magnificent glass-domed flower conservatory do require an entrance fee.
name: Gardens by the Bay

excerpt: Rainforest zoo with tram rides, trails & viewing platforms to see wildlife habitats & exhibits.
detail_description: Singapore Zoo is a lush rainforest zoo offering tram rides, walking trails, and viewing platforms to observe wildlife habitats and exhibits. The zoo provides an immersive experience for visitors to witness various animal species in naturalistic environments. Additionally, it hosts events such as urban lifestyle festivals featuring culinary delights, arts, entertainment, and live performances. For those seeking a romantic escape from crowded spots on Valentine's Day, the zoo offers a serene setting for a laid-back private time with nature.
name: Singapore Zoo

excerpt: Movie amusement park with sets & rides on themes from Hollywood to sci-fi, plus live entertainment.
detail_description: Universal Studios Singapore, located on Sentosa Island, is a sprawling movie-themed amusement park that offers an array of attractions and entertainment for visitors of all ages. With seven distinct zones inspired by popular films and television shows, the park boasts thrilling rides such as Battlestar Galactica and Jurassic Park Rapids Adventure. Guests can also explore intricately designed streets resembling Paris and Hollywood, shop for souvenirs, or enjoy a quick meal between adventures.
name: Universal Studios Singapore

excerpt: Huge observation wheel opened in 2008 for views of the city plus high tea & butler-serviced flights.
detail_description: The Singapore Flyer, the world's largest giant observation wheel, offers a unique experience for visitors to enjoy breathtaking views of the city. With its 28 glass cabins slowly revolving at 165m above ground level, it provides panoramic vistas of Marina Bay and its architectural landmarks. The observation wheel also offers various packages including high tea and butler-serviced flights, allowing guests to be pampered while taking in the stunning scenery.
name: Singapore Flyer

excerpt: The 70-ton merlion statue is one of the city's most iconic sights & is located in this park.
detail_description: Merlion Park is a must-visit destination in Singapore, known for its iconic 70-ton, 9-meter-tall merlion statue that spouts water into Marina Bay. This mythical creature with the head of a lion and the body of a fish has been an iconic landmark since it was built in 1972. The park is popular among both locals and tourists, offering picturesque photo opportunities and free entry.
name: Merlion Park

excerpt: This well-known, 2.2-km route features shopping malls & boutiques, plus restaurants & luxe hotels.
detail_description: Orchard Road in Singapore is a renowned 2.2-km stretch known for its abundance of shopping malls, boutiques, restaurants, and luxury hotels. Originally named after the fruit orchards and plantations that once occupied the area, it has evolved into a bustling shopping hub with over 5000 establishments. Visitors can explore a wide range of options from newer arcades like ION Orchard and Somerset 313 to established favorites such as Tangs and Ngee Ann City.
name: Orchard Rd

excerpt: Night zoo with tram rides and walking trails through rainforest past elephants, tigers & leopards.
detail_description: Night Safari, located in the Upper Seletar Reservoir, is the world's first nocturnal wildlife park. It offers tram rides and walking trails through a rainforest where visitors can spot creatures of the night such as elephants, tigers, and leopards. The park houses about 2500 animals that are best observed after sunset. Guests can embark on guided walking tours or take a tram safari to get up close to these fascinating creatures in their natural habitat.
name: Night Safari

excerpt: Verdant island with walking & cycling paths amid villages, old granite quarries & diverse bird life.
detail_description: Pulau Ubin is a lush island with scenic walking and cycling paths, surrounded by quaint villages, historic granite quarries, and a rich variety of bird species. It offers an offbeat destination for couples seeking a romantic getaway, with opportunities for proposals and intimate photography sessions. The island provides remarkable wildlife experiences and a chance to immerse in the old kampong atmosphere, as it is the last traditional village in Singapore where residents live without electricity using rustic methods.
name: Pulau Ubin

excerpt: Little India is a vibrant cultural enclave with temples and mosques, street art and brightly painted shophouses. Along the main drag, Serangoon Road, unfussy canteens and hip eateries sit next to shops selling gold jewelry, colourful silks and fresh flower garlands. Nearby, Mustafa Centre welcomes shoppers 24/7. The ethnic district is liveliest during Hindu celebrations like the Deepavali festival of lights.
detail_description: Little India is a lively cultural district in Singapore, featuring temples, mosques, street art, and colorful shophouses. Serangoon Road is the main thoroughfare where visitors can find a mix of casual eateries, trendy restaurants, gold jewelry shops, vibrant silks stores, and fresh flower garlands. Mustafa Centre offers 24/7 shopping nearby. The area comes alive during Hindu celebrations like the Deepavali festival of lights.
name: Little India

excerpt: Chinatown's maze of narrow roads includes Chinatown Food Street, with its restaurants serving traditional fare like Hainanese chicken rice, noodles and satay. Souvenir shops and indie boutiques dot the area, offering clothes, crafts and antiques, while Club Street is full of trendy wine bars. Cultural institutions here include the 1827 Sri Mariamman Temple and the ornate Buddha Tooth Relic Temple and Museum.
detail_description: Chinatown is a vibrant district in Singapore, known for its maze of narrow streets filled with traditional eateries, souvenir shops, and indie boutiques. Visitors can explore the area's rich cultural institutions such as the Sri Mariamman Temple and the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple and Museum. A visit to Maxwell Food Centre is a must for sampling local delicacies like Hainanese chicken rice and sugarcane juice.
name: Chinatown

excerpt: Large aquarium & resort featuring 800 species of marine life in a variety of habitats.
detail_description: S.E.A. Aquarium is a large aquarium and resort that houses 800 species of marine life in various habitats. It's located within Sentosa and offers a unique setting for photography, especially for wedding photos. The aquarium's lighting and reflective glass may require some adjustments to capture the perfect shot, but they also offer a wedding photography and videography package for couples who want professional images taken at this stunning location.
name: Singapore Oceanarium

excerpt: Lush, 10-floor retail complex with hundreds of shops & eateries, indoor gardens & a 40-m. waterfall.
detail_description: Jewel Changi Airport is a 10-floor retail complex featuring an array of shops, dining options, and indoor gardens. One of its main attractions is the lush indoor rainforest, complete with towering trees and a stunning 40-meter waterfall known as the Rain Vortex. The Shiseido Forest offers a sensory treat with its misty atmosphere and enveloping trees.
name: Jewel Changi Airport

excerpt: Design, science & technology exhibits in a distinctive, modern, flower-shaped building.
detail_description: Nestled among the towering skyscrapers of Singapore, the ArtScience Museum is a striking modern architectural marvel designed by renowned architect Moshe Safdie. Its distinctive lotus flower-shaped structure serves as an emblematic cultural landmark where art, science, culture, and technology converge. Collaborating with prestigious institutions and organizations worldwide, the museum presents exhibitions that explore the intersection of technology and culture.
name: ArtScience Museum

excerpt: Leafy, tropical nature reserve surrounding a hilltop with walking trails & a visitor centre.
detail_description: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve, located just 12 kilometers from Singapore city, offers a lush and tropical escape for nature enthusiasts. Spanning 1.64 square kilometers, this reserve is a haven for hikers and bikers with its scenic trails. The park boasts diverse flora and fauna, making it an ideal destination for families seeking an off-the-beaten-path experience in Singapore. With free entry, visitors can immerse themselves in the raw beauty of nature while exploring this green oasis.
name: Bukit Timah Nature Reserve

excerpt: Steel footbridge, opened in 2010, inspired by the curved form of the structure of DNA.
detail_description: The Helix Bridge, a stunning steel footbridge that opened its doors in 2010, is an architectural marvel inspired by the double-helix structure of DNA. Spanning 280 meters, this pedestrian walkway connects Marina Centre to Marina South and serves as a vital link to the iconic Marina Bay Sands resort.
name: The Helix Bridge

excerpt: White, sandy beach with a skate park, water sports & sports facilities, plus local food sellers.
detail_description: East Coast Park is a 15-kilometer stretch of sandy beach in Singapore, offering a variety of activities and amenities. It features a world-class Xtreme skateboarding park, water sports facilities, and sports amenities. The park also boasts smooth cycle paths and more than 300 kilometers of cycling and walking trails known as the Park Connector Network (PCN). Visitors can enjoy local food at the East Coast Lagoon Food Village or rent bicycles to explore the palm tree-fringed seaside.
name: East Coast Park
address: E Coast Park Service Rd, Singapore

detail_description: Esplanade Theatres on the Bay is a renowned performing arts center located near Marina Bay, offering an array of international shows and performances. With over 37,000 shows hosted and 26 million guests over its 15-year history, it's a hub for cultural experiences. The expansive 60,000 square meter complex includes theaters, concert halls, and a library dedicated to arts and culture.
name: Esplanade

excerpt: Museum exploring the history & cultures of Asia & their shaping of contemporary Singapore.
detail_description: The Asian Civilisations Museum (ACM) in Singapore is a unique institution dedicated to exploring the rich history and diverse cultures of Asia. With its extensive collection of over 13,000 artifacts from various regions such as China, Southeast Asia, South Asia, and West Asia, the museum offers an immersive experience into the multi-ethnic society of Singapore.
name: Asian Civilisations Museum
